{"id":"1802.08685","submitter":"Ehtibar Dzhafarov","authors":"Ehtibar N. Dzhafarov","title":"Quantum Mechanics with Contextually Labeled Observables","comments":"The paper is withdrawn by the author because it contains mistakes in\n  reasoning","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph math.QA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In the Contextuality-by-Default theory random variables representing\nmeasurement outcomes are labeled contextually, i.e., not only by what they\nmeasure but also under what conditions (in what contexts) the measurements are\nmade, including but not reducible to what other measurements are made\n\"together\" with the given one. We propose in this paper that the quantum\nobservables generating these random variables be labeled contextually as well,\nmaking the sets of the observables in different contexts disjoint. A quantum\nobservable is defined as a pair consisting of the observable's label and a\nself-adjoint operator in a Hilbert space. If a system is consistently connected\n(i.e., obeys \"non-disturbance,\" \"non-invasivenes,\" or \"non-signaling\"\nconditions), the observables measuring the same property in different contexts\nhave the same operator. A set of random variables possessing a joint\ndistribution is represented by commuting observables. The reverse, however, is\nnot true: random variables from different contexts do not have a joint\ndistribution irrespective of whether the corresponding observables commute. We\nillustrate this view of observables by deriving the Tsirelson bound for\nconsistently connected cyclic systems of rank 3.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 23 Feb 2018 14:34:56 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 6 Mar 2018 16:16:11 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 11 Mar 2018 13:47:31 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 5 Jun 2018 07:20:42 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 13 Aug 2018 11:14:23 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Sun, 9 Dec 2018 10:13:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-12-11"}
